  1. Recommended but optional interaction practice
    Allen, Blascovich, Tomaka, and Kelsey (1991) asked a sample of 45 people to perform a stressful task: count backwards by 13’s and 17’s in front of the experimenter while either alone, in the presence of a friend, or in the presence of their pet. To assess stress levels, the researchers recorded the subjects’ mean and maximum heart rates during the experiment:

    ps <- read.csv("https://www.macalester.edu/~ajohns24/data/PetStress.csv")
    Variable Meaning
    MaxHeartRate maximum observed heartrate in beats per minute (bpm)
    MeanHeartRate average heartrate (bpm)
    Condition C=control (alone),F=friend, P=pet

    1. Construct and summarize a visualization of the relationship between MaxHeartRate (the response variable) by MeanHeartRate and Condition. Include a representation of the trend using geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE).

    2. Consider the two models below. In the context of this study, explain the difference in the assumptions these models make about the relationships between the model variables.

      stress_model_1 <- lm(MaxHeartRate ~ MeanHeartRate + Condition, ps)
stress_model_2 <- lm(MaxHeartRate ~ MeanHeartRate * Condition, ps)

    3. Focus on stress_model_2. Use this model to construct an equation that captures the relationship between MaxHeartRate and MeanHeartRate for the pet group P. Be sure to write this in the form MaxHeartRate = a + b MeanHeartRate where you specify a and b.

    4. Interpret the MeanHeartRate:ConditionP coefficient in stress_model_2 (0.405). Do so in the context of this study.

    5. Which model do you think is more appropriate, stress_model_1 or stress_model_2? Support your argument with evidence from the plot as well as numerical evidence from the stress_model_2 coefficients. NOTE: We’ll explore a more rigorous way to address such questions later in the semester!



  1. Cars
    Consider the cars data which contains the sales price and other information for used Ford cars in St Paul and Dallas. To begin, we can model the price of a car by its mileage and age (in years) without an interaction:

    cars <- read.csv("http://www.macalester.edu/~ajohns24/data/FordsSub.csv")
car_model_1 <- lm(Price ~ Mileage + Age, cars)
summary(car_model_1)$coefficients
    ##                  Estimate   Std. Error   t value      Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  1.581683e+04 2.914668e+02 54.266314 4.188908e-137
## Mileage     -6.888903e-02 7.187744e-03 -9.584234  1.220109e-18
## Age         -4.809437e+02 8.168277e+01 -5.887946  1.304907e-08

    The corresponding model formula corresponds to the plane shown below:

    Price = 15820 - 0.069 Mileage - 480.09 Age

    By not including an interaction term, the above model assumed that the association between price and mileage does not differ by the age of the car. However, this assumption appears to be false. Instead, consider a model that includes an interaction between mileage and age:

    car_model_2 <- lm(Price ~ Age * Mileage, cars)
summary(car_model_2)$coefficients    
    ##                  Estimate   Std. Error   t value      Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept)  1.895467e+04 3.250928e+02  58.30543 1.061880e-143
## Age         -1.460909e+03 9.680060e+01 -15.09194  1.223559e-36
## Mileage     -1.219915e-01 6.793278e-03 -17.95768  2.776720e-46
## Age:Mileage  1.159252e-02 8.768120e-04  13.22122  2.405595e-30

    car_model_2 produces the following model formula:

    Price = 18950 - 1461*Age - 0.122*Mileage + 0.012 Age*Mileage

    Plotted below, this looks pretty good!

    1. Interpret the intercept coefficient, 18950. (This actually makes sense in this model!)

    2. Use car_model_2 to predict the price of a 5 year old car that has 10,000 miles on it.



  1. Car interactions

    By including an interaction term, car_model_2 assumes that the association between price and mileage may differ depending on the age of the car. Let’s explore what this means in practice.

    1. Use car_model_2 to construct formulas for the relationships between price and mileage for cars of different ages. Each of these should be of the form Price = a + b Mileage where you specify a and b. The first one is done for you. Complete the others using a similar technique.

      • 1 year old cars
        \[\begin{split} \text{Price } & = 18950 - 1461*1 - 0.122 * \text{ Mileage} + 0.012 * 1 * \text{ Mileage} \\ & = (18950 - 1461*1) + (-0.122 + 0.012*1) \text{ Mileage} \\ & = 17489 - 0.11 \text{ Mileage} \\ \end{split}\]

      • 5 year old cars

      • 10 year old cars


      These 3 lines are (roughly) captured in the plot below:


    1. Notice that the intercepts of these 3 models (ages 1, 5, 10) differ. Which of the following options is the best interpretation of these differences?
      • As the age of a car increases, the negative “impact” of mileage on price lessens.
      • As the age of a car increases, the negative “impact” of mileage on price becomes greater.
      • For cars with 0 mileage, average price increases as age increases.
      • For cars with 0 mileage, average price decreases as age increases.

    2. As seen in the plot and equations in part a, the slopes of these 3 models also differ! Which of the following options is the best interpretation of these differences?
      • As the age of a car increases, the negative “impact” of mileage on price lessens.
      • As the age of a car increases, the negative “impact” of mileage on price becomes greater.
      • For cars with 0 mileage, average price increases as age increases.
      • For cars with 0 mileage, average price decreases as age increases.

    3. In light of your work above, explain what the positive sign on the interaction coefficient indicates about the interaction between the mileage and age of a car.



  1. Politics
    In 2002 John McCain and John Kerry proposed new auto standards that would have forced manufacturers to increase fuel economy. Carl Levin proposed an amendment to the proposal that would delay any required increase in fuel economy. Hence a YES vote on the Levin amendment was good news for manufacturers. Senators also received contributions from auto manufacturers in 2002. This begs the questions: Who received the most auto contributions? Did it differ by political affiliation? How, if at all, were senators’ votes tied to their political affiliations and received auto contributions? In order to answer these questions, we’ll use the data set senators:

    senators <- read.csv("http://www.macalester.edu/~ajohns24/data/Senate.csv")

    The senators data contains the following measurements on each senator:

    Variable Description
    Vote 1 (voted YES) or 0 (voted NO)
    AutoCont dollars received from auto manufacturers
    Party D (Democrat) or R (Republican)
    others other variables indicate the senators’ names & states


    1. There are 100 senators, 2 from each state. Using dplyr() functions, find the following summary statistics:

      • the number of 2002 senators that were Democrats
      • the number of senators that voted for the amendment

    2. Construct and comment on a univariate visualization of the received contributions (AutoCont).

    3. There’s a clear outlier that received a lot of money from auto manufacturers. Use dplyr code (don’t simply scan the data by eye) to identify the senator, and the state they represent. Extra: IF you’re familiar with the auto industry, comment on why this state affiliation might not surprise us.

    4. Create senators_sub, a subset of the data that does not include this outlier. Confirm that the properties of your senators_sub data set match those below. IMPORTANT: Use the senators_sub data for the remainder of the homework.

      dim(senators_sub)
      ## [1] 99  6
      senators_sub %>% 
  summarize(mean(AutoCont))
      ##   mean(AutoCont)
## 1       12599.77

Optional extra exercises: The Macalester Paradox

In this section, you will explore the Macalester natural gas data (described below). The exercises are more open-ended in nature. It’s important to practice and build up confidence in such settings. In answering these questions, consider the Macalester administration to be your audience. That is, describe your analysis in a contextually meaningful way with as little statistics jargon as possible.

A few years back, Macalester invested in insulating three campus-owned houses: 180/182 Vernon Ave (address ), 1662 Princeton Ave (address ), and 1668 Princeton Ave (address ). Monthly data on energy use and other variables are available for each location at

https://www.macalester.edu/~ajohns24/data/MacNaturalGas.csv

Included are the following variables:

variable meaning
therms a measure of energy use (the more energy used, the larger the therms)
hdd “monthly heating degree days” is a measure of the amount of heating that the houses needed that month given the outside temperatures
address location (a, b, c)
renovated whether the location had already been renovated/insulated or not (yes, no)
month from 1 (January) to 12 (December)



NOTE

Because the houses were not fully instrumented, we only have information about the outside weather as measured by heating degree days (hdd). A quick peak confirms that high hdd reflects cold temperatures (cold temps require more heating) and that low hdd reflects warm temperatures (warm temps don’t require heating):



  1. An analysis
    The administration’s main question is whether or not the renovation paid off. That is, did the renovations result in lower energy usage? Analyze the data and present your findings to the administration. They are busy people, so keep your total discussion to 6 sentences or fewer. Further, make sure that your discussion and analysis incorporate the following pieces:

    • One visualization and one model that summarize the bivariate relationship between therms and renovated.
    • A second visualization and model that provide a more detailed look into this relationship (and that reveal the potentially misleading nature of the bivariate model). Keep this second model simple: incorporate only 1 additional predictor and do not include an interaction.
    • An explanation of the Simpson’s paradox your analysis has revealed with graphical evidence that supports your argument. For example, in the SAT example we explained that higher education funding doesn’t result in low SAT scores. Rather, states with higher education funding tend to have more students that take the SAT and that when more students take the SAT the average score tends to be smaller.
    • A final conclusion: did or did not the renovations result in energy savings?
